{{Infobox military conflict |partof = the [[Roman-Persian Wars]] |image = [[File:Roman-Persian Frontier, 5th century.png|300px|East Roman - Sasanian frontier]] |caption = East Roman - Sasanian frontier |conflict = East Roman–Sasanian War of 440 |date = 440 |place = [[Asia]] |result = Peace treaty: The Romans gives some payments to the Sasanians<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/yazdgerd-ii/ Encyclopaedia Iranica] "Upon ascending the throne, Yazdgerd II waged a war with the Roman empire, starting in 440 CE and with little success for either side (Greatrex, p. 2). The Romans, hard pressed on their southern front by the Vandal invasion and conquest of Carthage, sued for a quick end to war in return for payments to the Sasanians in order to defend the Caucusus."</ref> |casus = |combatant1 = [[East Roman Empire]] |combatant2 = [[Sasanian Empire]] |commander1 = [[Theodosius II]] |commander2 = [[Yazdegerd II]] |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= |}} {{Campaignbox Roman-Persian Wars}} The '''East Roman–Sassanid War of 440''' was a short conflict between the [[East Roman Empire]] and the [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanian Empire]]. The reason for its short ending was that the southern Roman provinces were being invaded by the [[Vandals]], which forced the East Romans to sue for a quick end to the war to focus on the Vandal invasion. The Sassanians were also paid some money in return for peace.<ref>http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/yazdgerd-ii</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Persian Empire: A Historical Encyclopedia [2 volumes]: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Kia|first=Mehrdad|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2016|isbn=9781610693905|location=Santa Barbara, CA|pages=282}}</ref>
== Background == The East Roman and Sassanid empires were frequently at war and this was largely rooted on religion as Persia - where [[Zoroastrianism]] prevailed - had been troubled by Christian [[proselytism]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Ashgate Research Companion to Byzantine Hagiography: Volume II: Genres and Contexts|last=Efthymiadis|first=Stephanos|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2014|isbn=9781409409519|location=Surrey, UK|pages=73}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Armenian Apocalyptic Tradition: A Comparative Perspective|last=Bardakjian|first=Kevork|last2=La Porta|first2=Sergio|publisher=BRILL|year=2014|isbn=9789004270244|location=Leiden|pages=387}}</ref> This period of conflict emerged after the reign of [[Yazdegerd I|Yazdgerd I]] who was known for his peaceful policy towards Byzantium and was even appointed guardian of the infant [[Theodosius II]], one of the [[Belligerent|belligerents]] of the war.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Late Antiquity|last=Nicholson|first=Oliver|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2018|isbn=9780198662778|location=New York|pages=1601}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars Ad 363-628, Part 2|last=Greatrex|first=Geoffrey|last2=Lieu|first2=Samuel|publisher=Routledge|year=2002|isbn=0415146879|location=London|pages=33}}</ref> This changed during the regimes of [[Shapur II]] and [[Yazdegerd II|Yazdgerd II]], who violently persecuted Jews, Christians, and Christian converts.<ref name=":0" /> It provoked a response from the East Roman empire, which sent troops against Persian forces after it failed to reverse Yazdgerd's policy peacefully.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of Wars, 3rd edition|last=Kohn|first=George|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=2007|isbn=0816065772|location=New York|pages=453}}</ref> The short-lived conflict, which some sources described as a stalemate,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Theodosius II: Rethinking the Roman Empire in Late Antiquity|last=Kelly|first=Christopher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2013|isbn=9781107038585|location=Cambridge|pages=11}}</ref> was reignited later in a series of hostilities (e.g. [[Justinian I#War with the Sassanid Empire, 527%E2%80%93532|Justinian's war with the Sassanids]]).<ref name=":1" /> These culminated in the Roman-Persian war during the time of [[Heraclius|Emperor Heraclius]] who defeated the Sassanid empire at the [[Battle of Nineveh (627)|Battle of Nineveh]] in 627 CE.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Military History of the Modern Middle East|last=McNabb|first=James Brian|publisher=Praeger|year=2017|isbn=9781440829635|location=Santa Barbara, CA|pages=10}}</ref>
